Combating climate change requires a comprehensive and coordinated strategy, including the implementation of relevant laws and regulations. Governments play an essential part in this endeavour by establishing the appropriate regulations and policies to minimize and adapt to climate change. Laws and regulations may include actions such as limiting emissions, instituting carbon pricing, and supporting renewable energy sources. These measures give people, corporations, and other organizations with clear guidelines and incentives to decrease their greenhouse gas emissions and transition to more sustainable practices. However, governmental enforcement is insufficient on its own. In ensuring right climate action, the commercial sector and other decentralized players also play a vital role. Businesses might, for instance, commit to reducing their carbon footprint, investing in renewable energy, and developing sustainable goods and services. Additionally, people and civil society groups may advocate for and encourage sustainable behaviors. In addition, it is essential to acknowledge that climate change is a global problem that needs collaboration and coordination across all levels of government and industries. Private or other decentralized actors should not be deterred from ensuring right climate action in the absence of governmental enforcement. By adopting sustainable practices and regulations, decentralized actors may set an example and lead the way, therefore encouraging governments to take more ambitious initiatives. In conclusion, combating climate change requires a comprehensive and coordinated strategy that involves the government's enforcement of proper laws and regulations, as well as the active engagement of commercial and other decentralized players. Private or other decentralized actors should not be deterred from ensuring right climate action in the absence of governmental enforcement. 